{"title":"pre-for-block-nvm-driver","slug":"NVM/pre-for-block-nvm-driver","date":"2019-12-03T07:26:50.000Z","updated":"2019-12-08T07:18:35.500Z","comments":true,"path":"api/articles/NVM/pre-for-block-nvm-driver.json","photos":[],"link":"","excerpt":"The Block Driver&#39;s TasksManaing PM space and providing a block interfaceprovide protectionassure consistency when lost power","covers":null,"content":"<h2 id=\"The-Block-Driver-39-s-Tasks\"><a href=\"#The-Block-Driver-39-s-Tasks\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"The Block Driver&#39;s Tasks\"></a><code>The Block Driver&#39;s Tasks</code></h2><h3 id=\"Manaing-PM-space-and-providing-a-block-interface\"><a href=\"#Manaing-PM-space-and-providing-a-block-interface\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Manaing PM space and providing a block interface\"></a><code>Manaing PM space and providing a block interface</code></h3><h3 id=\"provide-protection\"><a href=\"#provide-protection\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"provide protection\"></a><code>provide protection</code></h3><h3 id=\"assure-consistency-when-lost-power\"><a href=\"#assure-consistency-when-lost-power\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"assure consistency when lost power\"></a><code>assure consistency when lost power</code></h3><a id=\"more\"></a>\n<h2 id=\"DRAM内存模拟持久化设备的方法\"><a href=\"#DRAM内存模拟持久化设备的方法\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"DRAM内存模拟持久化设备的方法\"></a>DRAM内存模拟持久化设备的方法</h2><h3 id=\"dmesg-grep-BIOS-e820\"><a href=\"#dmesg-grep-BIOS-e820\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"dmesg | grep BIOS-e820\"></a><code>dmesg | grep BIOS-e820</code></h3><h3 id=\"sudo-su-vi-etc-default-grub\"><a href=\"#sudo-su-vi-etc-default-grub\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"sudo su; vi /etc/default/grub\"></a><code>sudo su; vi /etc/default/grub</code></h3><p><code>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=&quot;memmap=4G!12G&quot;</code></p>\n<p>begin 12 GB to 16 GB</p>\n<h3 id=\"update-grub-reboot\"><a href=\"#update-grub-reboot\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"update-grub; reboot\"></a><code>update-grub; reboot</code></h3><blockquote>\n<p>After the host has been rebooted, a new <code>/dev/pmem{N}</code> device should exist, one for each memmap region specified in the GRUB config. These can be shown using <code>ls /dev/pmem*</code>. Naming convention starts at /dev/pmem0 and increments for each device. The <code>/dev/pmem{N}</code> devices can be used to create a DAX filesystem.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"dmesg-grep-user\"><a href=\"#dmesg-grep-user\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"dmesg | grep user;\"></a><code>dmesg | grep user;</code></h3><h3 id=\"mount-file-system\"><a href=\"#mount-file-system\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"mount file system\"></a>mount file system</h3><blockquote>\n<p>Create and mount a filesystem using /dev/pmem device(s), then verify the dax flag is set for the mount point to confirm the DAX feature is enabled. The following shows how to create and mount an EXT4 or XFS filesystem.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<div class=\"highlight-wrap\"autocomplete=\"off\" autocorrect=\"off\" autocapitalize=\"off\" spellcheck=\"false\" contenteditable=\"true\"data-rel=\"BASH\"><figure class=\"iseeu highlight bash\"><table><tr><td class=\"gutter\"><pre><span class=\"line\">1</span><br><span class=\"line\">2</span><br><span class=\"line\">3</span><br><span class=\"line\">4</span><br><span class=\"line\">5</span><br></pre></td><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\">sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/pmem0</span><br><span class=\"line\">sudo mkdir /pmem</span><br><span class=\"line\">sudo mount -o dax /dev/pmem0 /pmem</span><br><span class=\"line\">sudo mount -v | grep /pmem</span><br><span class=\"line\">&gt; /dev/pmem0 on /pmem <span class=\"built_in\">type</span> ext4 (rw,relatime,seclabel,dax,data=ordered)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></div>\n<h3 id=\"Show-Capacity\"><a href=\"#Show-Capacity\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Show Capacity\"></a>Show Capacity</h3><ul>\n<li><p><code>sudo fdisk -l /dev/pmem0</code></p>\n</li>\n<li><p><code>sudo lsblk /dev/pmem0</code></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"Ref\"><a href=\"#Ref\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Ref\"></a>Ref</h2><p><a href=\"https://docs.pmem.io/getting-started-guide/creating-development-environments/linux-environments/linux-memmap\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Using-the-memmap-kernel-option</a></p>\n","categories":[],"tags":[{"name":"linux","slug":"LINUX","count":7,"path":"api/tags/LINUX.json"},{"name":"drivers","slug":"DRIVERS","count":6,"path":"api/tags/DRIVERS.json"}]}